text: hi everyone ethan e raisins here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new lil ugly
mane album volcanic bird enemy and the
voiced concern this is a brand new lp
from elusive rapper songwriter singer
multi-instrumentalist and producer
travis miller aka lil ugly mane a guy
who rocked the burgeoning world of
internet rap early on in the 2010s with
the release of mr thug isolation which
was a dark and twisted take on the
sounds of memphis rap and chopped and
screwed that we're seeing a really
healthy resurgence at the time the
project turned miller into an
underground king and an artist's artist
almost overnight and since then he's
pretty much been dodging the limelight
and the demands of fans looking to box
him in artistically he immediately began
dropping projects in this three-sided
tape series the super lengthy records
with all these connected pieces of
experimental rap cloud rap instrumental
hip-hop some of which was a mixed bag
for me but i absolutely loved the third
one 2015 was travis's last large proper
album under the little ugly maine name
but that's not to say he dropped off the
map entirely from there i could probably
spend 30 minutes in this video alone
going over the dozens of pseudonyms he's
released music under over the years a
lot of which push completely outside of
the hip hop sphere into industrial music
noise music power electronics but one of
his most prominent side projects
bedwetter does have a direct connection
to this lp since the track headboard
from this record was released at one
point as a bedwetter single which i
guess makes sense because that track was
a syrupy noise caked rocker with a
grunge twist stylistically doesn't
exactly scream out lil ugly mane but i
guess he's now comfortable with
expanding ugly maine's aesthetics even
further because that track and this
record culminate into some of the
strangest and most textured genre
fusions i've heard this year we're
talking fuzzy melty and hypnagogic
combinations of rock
wrap folk and trip hop throw in a
plunder phonic angle too with travis
being willing to sample just about
anything from jazz to string sections to
what sounds like the quaint music box
tune of an ice cream truck on the second
track here which makes it difficult to
point to an overall
style or direction for this record as
it's such a grab bag of different genre
combos but often travis is smoky and
dejected vocals combined with his love
of lo-fi aesthetics do become enough of
a common thread that laces through
everything which slightly becomes a
double-edged sword on this record
because travis is doing a lot more
singing than rapping here and his vocal
range respectfully is pretty limited to
the point where it kneecaps certain
songs like clapping seal where the vocal
straining is just a bit too much the
singing also comes across a bit too flat
emotionally on the song cold in here so
yeah there are ways in which volcanic
bird comes across a bit too constrained
despite being so boundary free
stylistically but even if this lp
doesn't leave a huge impact vocally
there is a lot to take in lyrically i
mean it's no surprise that travis has
pen game given his
years of putting out top-notch
experimental hip-hop but it's funny to
see how well he's able to work that into
more of a demented singer-songwriter
context like with the hilariously
contemptuous lyrics on cursor where for
the entire track travis is just wishing
uh horrible things on someone cursing
them quite literally the whole thing
sounds like the musical musings of a
hateful angry circus clown and maybe
that clown turns a little sad as well on
the song styrofoam where you can hear
travis singing if everything was
styrofoam
love would cost a dime on this honking
crackling ragtime jazz loop there are
other cuts here that go in more of an
instrumental hip hop direction like the
very loose jazzy and psychedelic beach
harness then swell aesthetically feels
like a lo-fi hip-hop twist on a
synth and rhythmic progression that
aphex twin would have cooked up in the
90s there's just something so calculated
and meditative about it i don't know
there are a few other slightly
derivative moments on the project like
stock car which uh i don't know why this
sounds like a dead ringer for a matthew
deer track but it kind of does but there
are plenty more exciting experimental
emotionally uh troubled tracks across
the rest of the record benadryl
submarine lives up to its title as it
sounds like i'm being submerged in a
murky body of water with all of its
cavernous reverbs delays and twisted
guitar loops the drums and melodic lead
vocals on the track bring sort of a trip
hop vibe to the table and the waves of
bass and synths that kind of transition
us into the hook show that travis still
has a very sharp ear for song structure
even in the midst of all of this sonic
filth the track vpn is a lo-fi gothic
piece of psychedelia with a boom bat
beat that i am very much here for then
broken ladder sees ugly mane
successfully flirting with some synth
pop on some throbbing synths and quirky
lo-fi tight beats meanwhile porcelain
slightly is one of several rock infused
cuts here this one is the closer and in
my opinion easily the best with its
cathartic righteous riffs it kind of
leaves the record off on a bit of a
positive note there are some other
highlights in the track list too but god
is this record so all over the place
what sticks out to you and what doesn't
is most likely going to be a very
individual experience so overall with
this project i liked it i liked it a lot
i thought it was really good it's
scatter shot yes but still insanely
creative as bold and as varied as those
three-sided tape projects but going in a
much different direction and you know
